comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Henry Houston Bonnell (1859-1926) was an 1880 Penn graduate (Class Prophet and recipient of the Spoon Award; cf. the Record for his year). After earning his BA, he worked for some years in publishing before retiring to concentrate on literary scholarship and philanthropy. His collection of works by and related to the Brontë family went after his death to the Brontë Parsonage Museum. A. Edward Newton, who advised both Bonnell and his widow to make the bequest, wrote of him:
Many years ago, nearer fifty than forty, I had a friend -- he is dead now -- who, like myself, was a member of a little club which devoted itself to the study of English literature. His name was Henry Houston Bonnell; unlike myself, he was not only pious, but good, really good. When I first knew him he was not rich, but he inherited wealth, and in between the various philanthropic activities to which he devoted his life he became a book-collector and a student of the English novel. He concealed from his friends -- at least from me -- the fact that he wrote hymns. I am glad of this. (Derby Day and Other Adventures (Boston: Little, Brown, 1934), p. 298-299)

comment.text:
No, although they did have a college in Chalons.  This is a stamp from the (diocesan) Petit seminaire de Chalons, founded by Louis-Antoine de Noailles, 1651-1729, bishop of Chalons, later archbishop of Paris, then given the cap in 1700, who was frequently accused (usually by Jesuits) of being a Jansenist.  His support for theological and doctrinal works condemned as Jansenist, and for individuals accused of Jansenism was never sufficiently countered by his seemingly lukewarm repudiation of the heresy.  He is frequently confused with other members of the Noailles family.

The Grand seminaire de Chalons, also under the patronage of Louis-Antoine de Noailles, later became a Lazarist school.

Châlons-sur-Marne became Châlons-en-Champagne by decree of June 11, 1995

comment.author: 40252563@N04
comment.text:
I asked a friend of Greek ancestry to help decipher the Greek line on this page, and here is what he had to say:
The first word is quite clear.  It's περι (peri) which means about, around, or concerning.  The second word is not so clear.  The 4th letter is written like a Greek L (lambda) but wouldn't make sense as such, so I'm quite sure it's a delta that has been written by someone who's script is influenced (not surprisingly) by the Latin style "d".  The second-to-last letter is an upper case eta (Η/η) while the rest of the inscription is lower case, and the final sigma is just plain weird looking.  I also suspect that Latin grammar has been mixed into the ending of this word as "εης" is not a nominal ending in any Greek declension, but sounds like a common Latin ending.  I believe the word is supposed to be "παιδαγωγιας" from which is derived the word "pedagogy". ( It's in its genitive form, which is correct.)  If my reconstruction is accurate, then this fellow was attempting to write something like "concerning education".  Furthermore, it is my firm belief that the writer received no higher than a letter grade of "C" in his Greek class.

comment.text: The Inscription above the line reads: "Sumad Remigio "Ho. practica del officio de curas "examind confessores "dotrina para penitentes = ano de 1690" This appears to be a reference to the book title "Practica Del Oficio De Curas, Y Confessores, Y Dotrina Para Penitentes" by Benito Remigio Noydens (1630-1685). The word "sumad" may be a form of the Spanish verb "sumar," one meaning of which is "being added to." Benito Remigio Noydens was a Spanish religious writer who was born in Antwerp. He was a member of the Order of Clerics Regular Minor [1]. Remigio's book was published in 1650 and was reprinted numerous times (most recently in 2010!). A copy of a 1674 edition of this book is in the rare book section of the Library of Congress [2]. A seventeenth edition, published in 1681 in Barcelona, is also known [3]. Perhaps the reference to the year 1690 is to yet another edition. The inscription below the line reads: "Diferencia entre lo temporal y Eterno, Auct. Eusebio Nirenbergens ==" This is a reference to the book title, "De la diferencia entre lo temporal y eterno; crisol de desengaños con la memoria de la eternidad, postrimerias humanas, y principales misterios divinos," by Juan Eusebio Nieremberg (1595-1658). Juan Eusebio Nieremberg was a Spanish Jesuit humanist, physicist, biographer, theologian, and ascetic writer who was a professor at the Jesuit Colegio Imperial de Madrid in Spain. This book was first published in Madrid in 1640 and went through numerous reprints and translations. [4] A copy of a 1678 edition of this book is in the rare book section of the Library of Congress [5]. An Italian translation ("La differenza il temporale e l'aeterno," by "Gio. Eusebio Nirenberg," published in Venice in 1683) is referenced here [6].
